<TITLE> Manila sells cheap rice direct to soldiers </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MANILA, April 18 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The Philippine government has started selling subsidised rice at military bases to ensure soldiers and their families have sufficient supply of cheap grain as global prices soar and the country scrambles to secure supplies. "This is for our soldiers and the retired veterans but the officers, they may not avail. The targets really are those who need it more," said military chief Gen. Hermogenes Esperon on Friday. "It was taken up in the cabinet. It was one of our recommendations from the armed forces and we are very happy that it has been granted by the President." Poorly-paid soldiers have been a traditional focus group for coup plotters in the Philippines and the military has been key in the overthrow of two presidents in the Southeast Asian country since 1986. President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo, whose approval ratings have slipped to the worst in over two years, has pulled out all the stops to ensure that Filipinos have access to cheap state-supplied rice, sold at 18.25 pesos a kilo, fearing anti-government demonstrations if poor people are forced to fork out more. The country is trying to pin down sufficient supplies to cover a traditional lean period in the third quarter and is having to pay more at each rice auction to buy its national staple and then sell it at a large discount to poor consumers. The Philippine government, which imports 10 percent of its rice requirements making it the world's largest importer of the grain, has spent $626 million so far on importing rice for this year and will shell out more at tenders this week and next month. Credit Suisse has calculated the country could lose up to $1.3 billion or 0.7 percent of Gross Domestic Product by importing up to 2.6 million tonnes of rice at climbing world prices and selling it at subsidised rates. Esperon said the subsidised rice sold in military shops would be 18 pesos a ki
